</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   GE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- GE Capital Auto Financial Services
said it acquired all of the auto installment loans held by
Empire Federal Savings of America, Buffalo, N.Y.
   A spokesman for GE Capital Auto, a unit of General
Electric Co.'s General Electric Capital Corp., said the
company jumped at the chance to make such a bulk purchase of
auto loans. Empire is currently held in conservatorship by
the federal Resolution Trust Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GE Capital Auto, with over $5.7 billion of auto-loan
assets, is a major servicer of auto loans for banks. A
spokesman said the portfolio was bought at a discount, but he
would not disclose the price. He said Empire's auto-loan
assets were about $900 million.
   GE Capital Auto said it plans to retain the 100 or so
Empire employees who were managing the portfolio. GE Capital
Auto is based in Barrington, Ill.
   General Electric's businesses, in addition to financial
services, include consumer and industrial products,
broadcasting and aerospace.
