WSJ900817-0042
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900817-0042.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS sank on rising Mideast tension and more
signs of recession and inflation. The Dow Jones industrials
fell 66.83 points to close at 2681.44. Long-term Treasury
bonds dropped 1 5/8 points. The bad economic news pushed the
dollar to a new low against the mark. Gold futures prices
surged $6.60 an ounce.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.4% in July, putting inflation at a
5.8% annual rate for 1990's first seven months, before oil
prices soared. Meanwhile, housing starts fell for the sixth
straight month, dropping 2.6% to their lowest level since
1982. The data show non-energy inflation persisting despite
economic weakness.
   ---
   Saudi Arabia and Venezuela intend to gradually boost their
oil output, by as much as 2.5 million barrels a day, whether
or not they win OPEC's approval at an emergency meeting that
the two nations are seeking.
   ---
   Sears Roebuck plans to eliminate thousands of jobs in the
next several months, in an effort to cut annual expenses by
more than $100 million.
   ---
   James River plans to sell or close units with $1.3 billion
in annual sales, nearly a fourth of the paper company. The
firm will take a charge against earnings of about $150
million.
   ---
   Cetus Corp.'s Robert Fildes quit as chief executive and
president, two weeks after an FDA panel rebuffed the firm's
cancer drug. Cetus also plans to lay off about 10% of its
staff.
   ---
   CBS Records' Walter Yetnikoff agreed to step down as chief
executive of the Sony unit in two years.
   ---
   Exxon sued the IRS, challenging the agency's claim that
the oil company owes $6.5 billion in back taxes. Exxon said
it expects to win but has set aside "adequate" reserves.
   ---
   Merrill Lynch and other firms are promoting a new
technique for companies to cut their capital-gains taxes that
is the subject of IRS scrutiny.
   ---
   Saatchi agreed to sell McCaffrey &amp; McCall back to the
unit's management for much less than the ad giant paid,
people close to the deal said. The lower price reflects
Saatchi's desire to streamline itself, as well as bad times
for ad agencies.
   ---
   Navistar posted a 79% drop in profit and a 10% decline in
revenue for the quarter that ended in July.
   ---
   Shearson agreed to accept less interest on a $500 million
loan to Prime Computer's parent in exchange for a bigger
equity stake in the company.
   ---
   Ameritrust plans to cut 780 jobs, 11.5% of its work force.
The bank company hopes to stem loan losses by reining in its
growth strategy.
   ---
   The New York Fed's backup power failed, delaying some bank
transactions and securities trading.
   ---
   The FTC accused the nation's largest coin-assessment firm
of making false and misleading claims.
   ---
   Canadian interest rates fell on the strength of the
nation's dollar. The Bank of Canada's bank rate reached its
lowest level since February.
   ---
   Austria will get nearly the same privileges in
high-technology trade that the U.S. accords to allies.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 138,850,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2681.44, off 66.83; transportation 939.78, off 21.90;
utilities 202.59, off 2.58.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3339.00, off
47.31.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.67, up 0.51; spot
index 131.77, off 1.29.
   Dollar: 147.25 yen, off 0.40; 1.5525 marks, off 0.0135.
</TEXT>
