<HL>
   Decision on Trump Plan May Be Delayed;
   Andersen Is Rehired to Deal With Casinos
   ----
   By Neil Barsky
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   X.TMP
</CO>
<IN>
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, N.J. -- Members of the New Jersey Casino
Control Commission hinted they would need more time to
evaluate Donald J. Trump's $65 million bank bailout plan, but
a lawyer for the developer pressed for a speedy decision on
the matter.
   Meanwhile Mr. Trump has rehired Arthur Andersen &amp; Co., his
longtime accounting firm, to work on the casino matter,
according to Securities and Exchange Commission filings. Mr.
Trump terminated his relationship with the firm in June
because of complaints from bankers about Andersen's
monitoring of Mr. Trump's business affairs. The Trump
Organization said yesterday that Andersen was rehired because
it has more expertise in the casino business than Kenneth
Levanthal &amp; Co., which will continue to oversee the Trump
bailout.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The gaming commission had scheduled meetings for yesterday
and today to approve the bank bailout, but two commissioners
suggested they might need an additional week to evaluate the
thousands of pages of documents related to the new financing.
   Thomas Cerabino, a lawyer for Mr. Trump, testified that
any delay would cause the banks to pull out of the bailout
proposal.
   The commission's approval of the bailout, which is needed
because of Mr. Trump's casino holdings, is the last step in
the restructuring of Trump Organization.
   New details of the bank agreement emerged during the
hearing, which was attended by Mr. Trump. Mr. Cerabino, of
the New York law firm Willkie Farr &amp; Gallagher, said the
accord, which would suspend about $850 million in interest
payments in exchange for collateral in Trump properties,
offers powerful incentives for Mr. Trump to sell assets as
quickly as possible. He referred to documents showing that
money generated from asset sales before June 30, 1991, would
retire interest payments at a rate of $5 for every $1
generated. Cash generated from assets sold between June 30,
1991, and June 30, 1992, could retire interest at a rate of
$2 for every $1 generated. The ratio continues to diminish
over time.
   Mr. Cerabino also said that a personal bankruptcy filing
by Mr. Trump would automatically trigger a default of the
loan agreement, but a default on a single asset wouldn't
necessarily trigger a default on the whole bank agreement. In
this way, Mr. Cerabino said, the total bailout plan is
insulated from the failure of a single asset.
   On Wednesday, the commission released documents showing
that on a short-term liquidation basis, Mr. Trump could have
anywhere from a negative net worth of $294 million to a net
worth of $281 million. As a "going concern," the report said,
Mr. Trump's assets would be valued at between $479 million
and $759 million.
   The New Jersey division of Gaming Enforcement, which is
part of the state attorney general's office, hinted in a
report yesterday that it would recommend to the commission
that it approve the bailout. "It may very well be that the
greatest hope for preserving remaining value {in the Trump
empire}, lies in a quick and efficient reorganization and
work-out process -- a privatized bankruptcy of sort --
outside the courtroom," the report stated.
   Another Trump lawyer, Nick Ribis, said the plan would
present Mr. Trump with "a realistic opportunity to solve
these problems on an ongoing basis."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900817-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900817-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Drought-Stricken Santa Barbara Turns
   To Desalination of Pacific Ocean Water
   ----
   By G. Pascal Zachary
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5A
</SO>
<CO>
   ION
</CO>
<IN>
WATER UTILITIES (WAT)
</IN>
<LP>
   The drought-stricken city of Santa Barbara, Calif., is
turning to the Pacific Ocean to help satisfy the thirst of
its parched residents.
   Santa Barbara, a coastal city of roughly 80,000 people
about 100 miles north of Los Angeles, agreed Tuesday to a
five-year contract with Ionics Inc. The deal calls for the
Watertown, Mass., company to build a desalination plant and
sell water produced by it to the city. The plant could supply
as much as a third of the city's water.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Water experts hailed Santa Barbara's decision as an
important spur to desalination, which generally is considered
too expensive and technically dicey to satisfy the
drinking-water needs of most cities. Desalination produces
drinking water by removing salt from sea water through a
filtration process called reverse osmosis. The process is
relatively expensive because it uses much electricity.
   "This certainly lends credibility to the effort," said
Lori Griggs, executive director for the Committee for Water
Policy, a lobbying group in San Francisco. "It will light a
fire that should prompt improvements in the technology."
   The city's decision also is a boost for Ionics, which
seeks to harvest a potentially huge market for desalinated
water in the parched West. Mainly, Ionics sells its
desalination plants and services to remote islands, or
communities in Florida that need to desalt brackish
groundwater. The company earned $3.6 million on sales of $109
million in 1989.
   "This gives Ionics a chance to prove their technology in
California coastal waters," said David Landecker, a Santa
Barbara City Council member. Mr. Landecker said Santa Barbara
still must decide how large a plant it wants Ionics to build.
The options under consideration would cost from $23 million
to $55 million and result in increases to city water bills of
anywhere from 42% to 67%.
   Rather than seeking to pioneer the process, Santa Barbara
is opting for desalination "out of desperation," Mr.
Landecker said. "We need water."
   A six-year drought has left this coastal city and its
environs drier than at anytime since the late 1860s. The city
and surrounding communities have imposed strict rationing
plans on residents. To make matters worse, the area isn't
part of the state's huge water-supply project. Its sole large
reservoir is at its lowest level ever and projected to go dry
in a year should the area suffer another winter of
below-normal rainfall.
   Ionics insists it can help Santa Barbara, a popular
tourist destination, stave off disaster. Desalination "is
practically viable and is looking more attractive as
alternatives, such as bringing in water from northern
California, are getting more expensive," said Arthur L.
Goldstein, Ionics's chairman. Already, several other water
agencies in California are studying a move to desalination.
In July, the giant Metropolitan Water District, which
provides more than half of the water used by 15 million
Southern Californians, began planning a demonstration
desalination plant.
   Next month, Marin County, which relies exclusively on
local wells and reservoirs, will begin testing drinking water
from an experimental plant designed to purify water from
nearby San Francisco Bay. Marin considers desalination "a
long-term water supply," but isn't likely to reap drinking
water from the bay before 1995, said Ronald Johnson, general
manager of the Marin Municipal Water District.
   Though California communities are scrambling for new water
sources to meet their growing populations and ward off
worries about a lengthening drought, basic economics could
well delay the acceptance of desalination. Desalination
remains a far costlier way to obtain water than traditional
sources, which cost roughly ten times less.
   "Technically, its not hard to do" said Ian Watson, a
desalination expert in Fort Myers, Fla. "But the economics of
sea-water conversion have to be dealt with. It's going to
cost more to make {drinking} water out of the ocean than
Californians have been used to paying."
   Even Santa Barbara is reluctant to describe its commitment
to desalination as anything more than an emergency measure.
"We're looking at this as a temporary supply," said Mayor
Sheila Lodge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900817-0013
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900817-0013.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Leonard Green
   Agrees to Purchase
   Carr-Gottstein Inc.
   ----
   By Sonia L. Nazario
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Leonard Green &amp; Partners said it agreed to
buy Carr-Gottstein Inc., Alaska's largest food-and-drug
retailer and wholesaler, for about $300 million.
   This is the first acquisition by Leonard Green &amp; Partners,
a merchant banking firm specializing in leveraged buy-outs
that was founded late last year by Leonard Green, formerly a
partner of New York-based Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen Ltd.
Leveraged buy-out activity in general has dropped since last
year's collapse of the junk-bond market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A spokeswoman for Leonard Green &amp; Partners said the
acquisition of Carr-Gottenstein, which should be completed in
the fall, wouldn't involve junk bonds. She wouldn't elaborate
on the nature of the financing.
   Mr. Green, who was credited with much of the success that
Gibbons, Green had with arranging LBOs in the 1980s, said he
left that firm because of "philosophical differences" with
his partners. Since setting up his own shop, he has been
struggling to match his prior track record; he has said his
goal is to complete between six and nine buy-outs, valued at
$100 million to $500 million each, in the next three years.
   Carr-Gottstein includes Carr's food and drug stores, the
J.B. Gottstein Co. wholesaling operation, the Oaken Keg
liquor stores, several shopping centers in Anchorage, Eagle
River, and Fairbanks and several other distribution-related
concerns.
   The acquisition provides for new stores and remodeling of
existing stores. Carr's General Manager John Cairns and its
vice president of operations, Mark Williams, will retain
their management positions, Leonard Green &amp; Partners said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900817-0012
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900817-0012.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Plunging Earnings
   Turn a Big Party
   Into a Little Bash
   ---
   N.V. Philips Trims Plans
   For Its 100th Anniversary
   As Cost Savings Measure
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5C
</SO>
<CO>
   PHG
</CO>
<LP>
   EINDHOVEN, The Netherlands -- Faced with plunging profits
in the first half of 1990 and an expected loss of 2 billion
guilders ($1.13 billion) for the year, N.V. Philips said it
has extensively cut back on lavish plans for the troubled
Dutch electronics giant's 100th anniversary celebration in
1991.
   Rather, Philips spokesman Jan van Schagen said the company
now plans to "commemorate the centenary in an unostentatious
and modest manner."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although plans hadn't yet been finalized, at one time they
included a street carnival in Eindhoven as well as two major
company exhibits, Mr. Van Schagen said.
   "Those are definitely off," said Mr. Van Schagen. "We feel
the situation in which we now are and the way we celebrate
these festivities ought to be in some proportion."
   Originally, Philips had been planning to spend "tens of
millions" of guilders on the anniversary, Mr. Van Schagen
said but added he had no estimate for the costs of the
currently planned celebrations.
   On Aug. 9, Philips reported that its net income from
ordinary activities plummeted to 43 million guilders in the
first half of 1990 from 420 million guilders in the
year-earlier period. Including extraordinary items, Philips
had a total net income of 373 million guilders in the first
half of 1990 compared with 458 million guilders in the first
half of 1989.
   Philips is maintaining an earlier forecast that it will
have to spend 2.7 billion guilders on restructuring efforts
and lay off close to 10,000 workers, mostly in its Western
European operations. The restructuring charge will result in
a loss of about 2 billion guilders for the year, according to
Philips' forecast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
